## Keeping docs in sync

`README.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, `.claude/memory/project-context.md`, `.claude/docs/architecture.md` and `.claude/docs/conventions.md` are part of the codebase — they move in the same change as the code that affects them, not deferred to a separate cleanup PR. A stale doc is worse than no doc.

Before closing a change, check whether it touches anything in the left column below and update the matching doc(s) in the same commit. The rows are illustrative — adapt to this project's actual doc surfaces and remove rows that don't apply.

| If you changed... | Update... |
|---|---|
| Public API / CLI surface (commands, flags, exported functions) | `README.md`, `CLAUDE.md` |
| Architecture, data flow, directory structure | `.claude/docs/architecture.md` |
| Code style, naming patterns, error-handling conventions | `.claude/docs/conventions.md` |
| External dependencies, env vars, setup steps | `README.md`, `.claude/docs/architecture.md` |
| Domain rules, version floors, constants the business cares about | `.claude/memory/project-context.md` |
| Non-obvious decision or gotcha worth remembering | `.claude/memory/MEMORY.md` (not the docs above) |

`MEMORY.md` is not a substitute for these docs — it captures non-derivable context (decisions, gotchas, past incidents). If you find yourself wanting to write a how-it-works note in memory, write it in the docs instead.
